Lab From A Chip is a DIY intervention in lab-on-a-chip technology inspired by science and technology studies (STS) and microbiological technique. It's part of Ross Dalziel's PhD research project, Critical Kits at the Division for BioMedical Life Sciences at Lancaster University (BLS) and makerspace DoESLiverpool making add-ons for the Foldscope, a folding paper microscope by Prakash Labs.
"A lab-on-a-chip is a device that integrates one or several laboratory functions on a single integrated circuit of only millimeters to a few square centimeters" Wikipedia

It's a review of bio-technology & microbiological technique, the material practices of doing bio-science. We've packaged up the existing, friendly & cheap Foldscope; alongside the innovative practice of scientist and engineer Alexandre Benedetto and his colleagues at BLS.

They make cheap robust consistent PDMS microfluidic channels to watch nematode worms using old vinyl audio records as moulds. Our add-ons make the process accessible to DIY newcomers & let you follow the practice using vinyl fragments, surplus electronics and Euglena gracilis, a light sensitive algae.
Lab From A Chip:
Foldscope Add-Ons

Now setup your phone with the Foldscope and see if our algal friends have found their way into our microfluidic channels. We've found that the vinyl record technique is the most rewarding, as you get to see our Euglena gracilis moving along the grooves; and understand their scale compared to yours.

With your phone setup you could try shining the LED included and see how they respond. These organisms are mixotrophic in that they ingest food but also photosynthesise, so like plants 'make' food from sunlight and so respond to it.

Have a think what other ordinary stuff we have in our homes and workplaces that might have tiny spaces the size of record grooves or silicon chip logos? What about textiles or the surface of a battery or a splinter of wood? Once you put yourself in the Algae's position the human engineered world and all it's 'freedoms' becomes vast and almost terrifying in it's scale and impact yet easy to forget and make invisible. Think about what histories might have been necessary to make these spaces and indeed this kit possible.
